                    <span>Fabian is on the money.  Jeff Unsel (above), you're a perfect example of the problem.  Get out of IT and try selling cars or something.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Could be better, but not much</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
                      <span>5</span>
                      /
                      <span>5</span>
                      votes <span class="ItemCaption">Reviewed: </span>
                      <span>2003-02-07</span>
                    </div>
                    <span>Ever wondered why is it so difficult to put rich data into the relational model, or why so much of database logic keeps being badly manipulated by application programs instead of by DBMS?  Ever felt SQL was too verbose, or complex, or illogical, and simply arbitrarily limited?  Mr Pascal helps us organise our grips against current DBMSs and hope for a better future.<p>This book analyses common database problems every professional with more than a few months in the field has already faced, and relentlessly trace them to failures in SQL implementations or in the SQL language itself.  A real mind-opener in the current state of the field, where from press to shop everything is dominated by vendors but few true critics survive.</span>
                  
                    <div class="CustomerReviewSummary">Not professional</div>
                    <div>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Rating: </span>
                      <span>1</span>
                      <span class="ItemCaption">Helpful: </span>
